  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated Nutrition, Food Security and WASH Drought Response in the Most Affected Districts of Bamyan and Daikundi Provinces.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Central Highlands region in Afghanistan has been experiencing a prolonged dry spell, due to below-average precipitation over the winter period. Due to a short agricultural season, timely precipitation is essential for agricultural production and water systems in the region, without which urgent action is needed for those affected. The complex, slow onset crisis has led to a steep increase in number of malnourished children and pregnant and lactating women (PLW) which, coupled with a lack of coverage and capacity by the existing health system to meet the needs in the region, underlines the urgent importance of Medair&#x2019;s multi-sectoral intervention to reduce preventable mortality and morbidity amongst vulnerable groups. 

The proposed project aims to respond to the drought affected population and build community resilience in targeted districts of Daikundi and Bamyan Provinces through provision of outreach nutrition services, water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) interventions, and activities to improve food security and livelihoods. Building upon Medair&#x2019;s seventeen years of experience in the Central Highlands, the project intends to improve utilization of nutrition services by mothers, PLW and children under five, improve access to water under drought conditions to reduce vulnerability to water-related and other preventable diseases, and increase food security through community disaster risk reduction (DRR) based cash for work (CFW) activities with an unconditional cash component for the most vulnerable households.. Protection is addressed through mainstreamed mitigation strategies to prevent exposure to and/or created risks for beneficiaries as a result of the project. In addition, mainstreamed protection will ensure project activities are meaningful, accessible and safe for beneficiaries.</narrative>
  </description>
